Integration test (Rust port of `test/struct.test.ts`) verifying that `emit_struct` correctly reproduces every `@literal` block from the real `dict.steno` corpus (read from the repo root, not a fixture) when replayed through a smart-indent editor simulation.

It depends on `dict.steno` at `<repo root>/dict.steno` via `CARGO_MANIFEST_DIR`-relative path — if that file moves or its `@literal` entries change, `found_the_data_structure_entries` (which asserts >5 such entries) and `reproduces_every_literal_block` can fail or silently pass on fewer cases. The `intended()` helper encodes the expected auto-indent editor behavior: tabs become 4 spaces per level, and blank lines are dropped entirely, matching the "v2 emitter skips blanks" behavior — this must stay consistent with whatever `emit_struct`/`interpret` under `SMART_INDENT` actually do, since the test compares byte-for-byte against `struct_text(&e.template)` run through this transform.

`reproduces_every_literal_block` is the main correctness test: for each literal entry, it runs `emit_struct(&e.template)` through `interpret(..., SMART_INDENT)` and diffs the resulting buffer against `intended(struct_text(&e.template))`.

`never_types_a_bare_closing_brace` hardcodes dependence on a specific corpus entry with stroke `"STKWR-RBGT/S"` — if that stroke is renamed or removed from `dict.steno`, this test fails with "STKWR-RBGT/S present" rather than a meaningful assertion failure. It asserts two invariants about `emit_struct`'s event stream: no `Event::Text("}")` is ever emitted (closing braces must come from auto-indent/editor behavior, not typed literally), and at least one `Event::Key { key: KeyName::Down, .. }` occurs (navigation is used to exit nested blocks rather than typing structure closers).